library(shiny) library(bslib) #library(gridExtra) library(plotly) library(markdown) rw_proddata <- read.csv("ac24res_v5_production.csv") rw_impov_grp <- read.csv("ac24res_v5_cit_tbyt.csv") rw_hoggdata <- read.csv("distribution_indicators.csv") link_gitlab <- tags$a("gitlab", href = "https://gitlab.com/aschniedermann/pandots", target = "_blank") link_gdoc <- tags$a("googledoc", href = "https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gKOqGy08cAQfdV-0sTJy-Whdw8gEi391G0B0vWx4MKw/edit#heading=h.r67ikr567okf", target = "_blank") # shinylive::export("C:/Users/trantor/Documents/git_projects/pandots/r_project/shinyapp", "C:/Users/trantor/Documents/git_projects/pandots-shiny/docs") # Definition of plot titles and Axis labels lblxaxisPanMon <- "Pandemic month (from January 2020)" lblyaxisPortion <- "Monthly portion (in %)" lblyaxis2Portion <- "Monthly portion of total (in %)" lblTitleProd <- "Monthly proportions of different document types" lblRefTypedAvgTitle <- "Monthly average number of reference of document type group and Covid-19 relatedness of citing item" lblyaxisAbsolute <- "Average reference count" lblRefTypedRateTitle <- "Portion of references that go to Covid-19 related research (citeditem)" lblTitleplot_refstypebytypeC <- "Reference / cited item is about Covid-19" lblTitleplot_refstypebytypeNC <- "Reference / cited item is not about Covid-19" lblProdExpl = "

Results

This panel shows the monthly output of medical research publications since January 2020. For each month, the mix of the document type groups results in 100%, so that the monthly relationship between the different genres becomes visible. if the Covid-19 related research is selected, the graph reveals how researchers used different formats differently when they addressed the pandemic. However, the comparatively low absolute output for the first three months should be considered.

Interestingly, editorials, letters, and news items which we summarized as Problems played an important role in the scholarly crisis response. But in contrast to Preprints, these formats received far less public attention.

In comparison, there are almost no genre dynamics in the corona unrelated research. The rise in Preprints since month 33 is due to the indexing of additional preprint servers by OpenAlex

" lblRefResults = "

Results

The figures provide an overview over the number of references of the different publication types during the pandemic. The upper plot compares the average number of references between publications about Covid-19 (blue) and those that do not cover the pandemic (green). Despite a slow inflation, the number of references remains roughly consistent for Covid-19 unrelated research. In contrast, Covid-19 related research used fewer references in the beginning of the pandemic (13 in May 2020 for Articles), but grew steadily over time (28 in January 2022).

The lower figure shows the share of references that itself refers Covid-19 related research. For articles, this is negligible for Covid-19 unrelated research, while it accounts for over the half of references for Covid related research for almost the whole timespan. The amount is even higher for Preprints: 71% of all references of Covid-19 related Preprints from Janmuar 2021 were themselves about Covid-19 related content.

" lblRefTbTResults = "

Results (recheck calcs, as values seem to be wrong!!!)


The figures show the document type groups of referenced items to extend the perspective of the previous tab. The upper graph shows the distribution of types among references about Covid-19 research. If the produced item is also about Covid-19 (same topic citation), the shares of the different document types among the references offer some dynamics. For almost the whole timespan, a bigger share of Covid-19 related references went to Problems, rather than Preprints.

" lblRefHoggResults = "

Results

The figures show some indicators about the citation distribution to each document type group. The HHI provides an additional overview over the concentration of references to a few cited items. Its decrease reveals that there have been a small but influential number of items in the beginning of the pandemic, while citations were spread more evenly later on

" # Define UI for app that draws a histogram ---- ui <- page_navbar( title = "PanDots", bg = "black", nav_panel( "Introduction", # card_header("Introduction"), full_screen = TRUE, includeMarkdown("texts/intro.md") ), nav_panel( "Production", card_header("The production of medical research during the Covid-19 pandemic by document type group"), full_screen = TRUE, sidebarLayout( sidebarPanel( selectInput("prod_citingcorona", "Item is about Covid-19", unique(as.character(rw_proddata$citingcorona)) ), selectInput("prod_types", "Genre group", unique(as.character(rw_proddata$citing_type)), selected = unique(as.character(rw_proddata$citing_type)), multiple = TRUE ), HTML(lblProdExpl), width = 3), mainPanel(plotlyOutput("plot_prod"), DT::dataTableOutput("prod_table"), width = 9) ) ), nav_panel( "References: Overview", card_header(""), full_screen = TRUE, sidebarLayout( sidebarPanel( selectInput("ref_articletype", "Document type group of citing item:", unique(as.character(rw_proddata$citing_type)) ), HTML(lblRefResults), width = 3 ), mainPanel( includeMarkdown("texts/RO_A.md"), plotlyOutput("plot_refstypedavg"), includeMarkdown("texts/RO_B.md"), plotlyOutput("plot_refstypedport"), width = 9 ) ) ), nav_panel( "References: Document Types", card_header("References of corona-based research: type by type references"), full_screen = TRUE, sidebarLayout( #fillable = TRUE, sidebarPanel( selectInput("cxc_citingcorona", "Produced item: Corona-relatedness", unique(as.character(rw_impov_grp$citing_corona)) ), selectInput("cxc_citingtype", "Produced Item: Document Type", unique(as.character(rw_impov_grp$citing_type_agg)) ), selectInput("cxc_ratetype", "Calculation of shares:", c("Set-based" = "percent_setbased", "Item-based" = "percent_itembased") ), HTML(lblRefTbTResults), width = 3 ), mainPanel( plotlyOutput("plot_refstypebytypeC"), plotlyOutput("plot_refstypebytypeNC"), width = 9 ) ) ), nav_panel( "References: Concentration", card_header("Distributions of references by document type group & relative Herfindahl Hirschman Index"), full_screen = TRUE, sidebarLayout( #fillable = TRUE, sidebarPanel( selectInput("hogg_citedType", "Cited Item: Document Type", unique(as.character(rw_hoggdata$cited_type)) ), selectInput("hogg_indicator", "Indicator:", c("relative Herfindahl-Hirschman Index (in %)" = "herfindahl_relative", "absolute Herfindahl-Hirschman Index" = "herfindahl_absolute", "Hogg's Skewness" = "hogg_skewness", "Hogg's Kurtosis" = "hogg_kurtosis", "Pearson Coefficient" = "pearson_coeff" ) ), HTML(lblRefHoggResults), width = 3 ), mainPanel( plotlyOutput("plot_refshoggT"), plotlyOutput("plot_refshoggF"), width = 9 ) ) ), nav_menu( title = "Links", align = 'right', nav_item(link_gitlab), nav_item(link_gdoc) ) ) server <- function(input, output) { # -------------------------------# # ------Production of items------# # -------------------------------# output$plot_prod <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_proddata[rw_proddata$citingcorona == input$prod_citingcorona & rw_proddata$citing_type %in% input$prod_types,], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~percent, color=~citing_type, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% add_trace(y= ~portion_by_corona, yaxis = "y2", name = 'Monthly share', type = "bar", marker = list(color = '#F3F3F3', opacity = 0.1)) %>% layout(yaxis2 = list(side = "right", title=lblyaxis2Portion), showlegend=FALSE, title=lblTitleProd, xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title=lblyaxisPortion, overlaying = "y2"), barmode = 'overlay', hovermode = "x unified" ) }) output$prod_table <- DT::renderDT( DT::datatable( rw_proddata[rw_proddata$citingcorona == input$prod_citingcorona & rw_proddata$citing_type %in% input$prod_types,], rownames = FALSE, colnames = c("Pandemic Month","has Corona","Document Type","References (avg)","Items per Type","Items per Month","Portion per Month (in %)","Portion per Corona (in %)","Portion of all (in %)") ) ) # ---------------------------------------# # ------References General Overview------# # ---------------------------------------# output$plot_refstypedavg <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_proddata[rw_proddata$citing_type %in% input$ref_articletype,], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~avg_refcount, color=~citingcorona, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=lblRefTypedAvgTitle, xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title=lblyaxisAbsolute), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) output$plot_refstypedport <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_proddata[rw_proddata$citing_type %in% input$ref_articletype,], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~avg_refrate_to_corona, color=~citingcorona, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=lblRefTypedRateTitle, xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title=lblyaxisPortion), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) # -----------------------------------# # ------References Type by Type------# # -----------------------------------# output$plot_refstypebytypeC <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_impov_grp[rw_impov_grp$citing_corona == input$cxc_citingcorona & rw_impov_grp$citing_type_agg %in% input$cxc_citingtype & rw_impov_grp$cited_corona == 'true',], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~get(input$cxc_ratetype), color=~cited_type_agg, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=lblTitleplot_refstypebytypeC, xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title=lblyaxisPortion), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) output$plot_refstypebytypeNC <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_impov_grp[rw_impov_grp$citing_corona == input$cxc_citingcorona & rw_impov_grp$citing_type_agg %in% input$cxc_citingtype & rw_impov_grp$cited_corona == 'false',], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~get(input$cxc_ratetype), color=~cited_type_agg, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=lblTitleplot_refstypebytypeNC, xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title=lblyaxisPortion), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) # -----------------------------------# # ------References Concentration-----# # -----------------------------------# output$plot_refshoggT <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_hoggdata[rw_hoggdata$citingcorona == "true" & rw_hoggdata$cited_type %in% input$hogg_citedType, ], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~get(input$hogg_indicator), color=~citedcorona, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=paste(input$hogg_indicator, "of references by Covid-19 related items to", input$hogg_citedType), xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title="value"), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) output$plot_refshoggF <- renderPlotly({ plot_prod <- plot_ly(rw_hoggdata[rw_hoggdata$citingcorona == "false" & rw_hoggdata$cited_type %in% input$hogg_citedType, ], x=~citing_date) %>% add_trace(y=~get(input$hogg_indicator), color=~citedcorona, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines') %>% layout(showlegend=FALSE, title=paste(input$hogg_indicator, "of references by Covid-19 unrelated items to", input$hogg_citedType), xaxis=list(title=lblxaxisPanMon), yaxis=list(title="value"), hovermode = "x unified" ) }) } shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

# Overview over references of corona-related research
Publications have reference list to show on what previous works they are based. The type and amount of references a publication has tells us something about the evidence-based that is behind the claims of a research article. The next two figures provide an insight into two different dimensions.

The first figure just shows the average number of references per month, depending on whether the item is about Covid-19 (blue line) or not (green line). If *Articles* are chosen, one can see a small but constant increase, indicating that the number of references rises in general. In contrast, Covid-19-related articles had a much smaller but constantly rising reference count since the beginning of the pandemic. These dynamics are similar for the other items too. Notably, *Syntheses* revolve around 80 references per item which is the highest level.

name: texts/RO_B.md
content: The second figure shows what portion of references of any item was itself about Covid19-related research. In the case of *Articles*, references to Covid-related research made up half the reference list since April 2020 if the citing article is itself about Covid-19 (blue line). Not surprisingly, if the citing article is itself not about Covid-19, it only rarely referenced research that is. In contrast, over 72% of the references made by Covid-19 related *Preprints* are themselves about Covid-19 rekated content.

name: texts/intro.md
content:
# Analysis of Pandemic Document Types (PanDots)
**Alexander Schniedermann, Arno Simons**  
German Centre for Higher Education Research and Science Studies ([DZHW](https://www.dzhw.eu/) )  
Technische Universitt Berlin ([TU Berlin](https://www.tu.berlin/) )  
*Contact: schniedermann@dzhw.eu*

# Introduction

The Covid-19 pandemic required to quick addressation and reaction by scientific research, especially in biomedicine. As a result, usual behaviors and patterns in publishing changed substantially during the course of the pandemic. Most notably, medical research used preprinting in an unprecendented way [Fraser et al. 2021](https://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.3000959). Preprints are scientific articles that have been made public before any type of peer review has been performed. For this reason, they are often considered as preliminary, somwhat less robust, and their results should be taken with care [see Simons and Schniedermann 2023](https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783110776546-003/html?lang=de). In contrast, review articles and systematic reviews in particular aggregate previous research into a bigger picture. They are often used to combine results from multiple studies about with a similar research question in order to draw an overall or *final* result regarding that question. Therefore, results of reviews are considered as more robust and are usually placed first in the hierarchy of (medical) evidence [Schniedermann et al. 2022](https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/oa-edit/10.4324/9781003188612-8/top-hierarchy-guidelines-shape-systematic-reviewing-biomedicine-alexander-schniedermann-clemens-bl%C3%BCmel-arno-simons). Besides epistemic characteristics such as preliminarity or robustness, document types may also represent particular scholarly functions. For example, comments on the current trends and problems in the field are published as letters to the editor by researchers, or as editorials by academic journals. Especially in medicine, important observations may also be published as case study before any systematic analysis is possible or feasable.

All in all, scholars have already argued how different stages of scientific discourses bear certain types of formal communication or publication genres [Cohen and Schnalle 1986](https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-94-009-4498-5).
While the bibliometric analysis of pandemic science has put much attention to preprints, no studies assessed thebroader contexts of publication genres during the Covid-19 pandemic so far. For this reason, this project combines the relevant data in an accessible and explorative way.

# Data
The basic underlying dataset are medical publications indexed in PubMed and assigned a PubMed identifier (PMID). In early 2024, the complete metadata record of PubMed as of December 2023 was retrieved. Since January of 2020, the first year of the pandemic, the set provides x unique PMID's. Since PubMed does not include preprint articles and only indexes citation links to other PubMed items, the database has been matched to OpenAlex in a second step. The OpenAlex snapshot of February 2024 as provided by the [German Competence Network Bibliometrics](https://www.bibliometrie.info) has been used for this purpose. After the matching, the dataset consists of x items.

**Preprints**  
Preprints are identified on the basis of registered source titles in OpenAlex. In contrast to the rest of the set, preprints do not necessarily have a PMID as they might not be registered in PubMed at all. In addition, preprints which are not from the medical domain are less comparable to the PubMed Set. For this reason, only those repositories were kept in the sample that have at least 15% of their preprints labeled as "Health Sciences" [topic in Open Alex](https://docs.openalex.org/api-entities/topics). Further details on the selection procedrue can be found in the openalex_exploration gitlab.
Therefore, the list of covered servers are: 
- 'bioRxiv (Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory)'
- 'Research Square (Research Square)'
- 'Europe PMC (PubMed Central)',
- 'Authorea (Authorea)'
- 'medRxiv (Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory)',
- 'Authorea'
- 'HAL (Le Centre pour la Communication Scientifique Directe)'
- 'Zenodo (CERN European Organization for Nuclear Research)'
- 'PsyArXiv (OSF Preprints)'
- 'OSF Preprints (OSF Preprints)'

**Identification of Corona-related Research**  
Whether a publication was about Covid-19 or not was identified in two steps. First, any publication that is assigned a Covid-19 related MeSH term was marked as Covid-19 related (see [NLM 2021](https://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/techbull/nd20/nd20_mesh_covid_terms.html) ). However, since there is some indexing time lag at NLM which also not indexes preprints at all, a title and abstract based system has been used in asecond step. Based on the Covid-19 related MeSH terms, titles and abstracts have been screened as well, using the following fulltext search in postgresql: `to_tsquery('english','coronavirus | (corona <-> virus) | covid | (sars <-> cov <-> 2) | sars-cov-2 | sars-cov2 | (sarscov <-> 2) | sarscov-2 | sarscov2 | ncov2019 | (ncov <-> 2019) | ncov-2019 | 2019ncov | (2019 <-> ncov)')`. Evaluating the second against the first approach, an overall precision of 0.9330 , recall of 0.9622 and F1-Score of 0.9474 have been retrieved. Therefore, the title and abstract based screening provided as solid classification approach.

# Methods
**Citation distributions**  
For the analysis of the dynamics in the citation distributions, Hogg's skewness and kurtosis for non-normally distributed data has been used [Bono et al. 2019](https://www.mdpi.com/2073-8994/12/1/19) . In addition, the Herfindahl Hirschman Index (HHI) was calculated for analyzing the citation concentration of the evidence-base of Covid-19 related research. To compare the HHI of different months, it is reported as monthly proportion of the maximum possible HHI of that month. The maximum HHI represents the hypothetical case in which a single article would receive all citations that were made that month. In contrast to other bibliometric analyses that use HHI, not the citation concetration of the cited articles was calculated. Rather, all citations that were made during a single month were conceived as the 'market', or evidence-base of research published that month [see Larivire et al. 2009](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/asi.21011) .

# Main Results
Among the many insights that can be obtained from the data, we identified three core takeaways...
